subsection.p:
With one sign convention, define the electromagnetic field 2-form
\boxed{F=\mathcal B+\mathcal E\wedge dt.}
Then
\begin{aligned} d_4F &= d\mathcal B+dt\wedge\left(\mathcal B_t+d\mathcal E\right). \end{aligned}
Therefore
\boxed{d_4F=0}
is exactly the pair
d\mathcal B=0,
d\mathcal E+\mathcal B_t=0.
So the no-magnetic-monopoles law and Faraday's law combine into one space-time equation:
\boxed{d_4F=0.}

The other pair also combines. Define
\boxed{G=\mathcal D-\mathcal H\wedge dt.}
Then
\begin{aligned} d_4G &= d\mathcal D+dt\wedge(\mathcal D_t-d\mathcal H). \end{aligned}
Using
d\mathcal D=\mathcal Q
and
d\mathcal H-\mathcal D_t=\mathcal J,
we get
\boxed{d_4G=\mathcal Q-dt\wedge\mathcal J.}
The right side is the space-time current 3-form:
\boxed{\mathscr J=\mathcal Q-dt\wedge\mathcal J.}
So the second pair becomes
\boxed{d_4G=\mathscr J.}

The space-time form of Maxwell's equations is therefore
\boxed{d_4F=0,}
\boxed{d_4G=\mathscr J.}

subsection.md:
\boxed{\begin{aligned}
&\text{Local derivatives describe what happens inside.}\\
&\text{Boundary integrals record what crosses or circulates outside.}\\
&\text{Differential forms keep the dimensions and orientations honest.}
\end{aligned}}
